    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I was just trying to inject a bit of whimsy into the conversation, but I suppose it didn't quite land. By \"goblin-proof,\" I meant a locking mechanism that's resistant to the kinds of concurrent access issues that might arise in a high-traffic system, where a group of goblins might be trying to jostle for position.\n\nIn reality, I was suggesting a distributed lock service like Redis or ZooKeeper, which can provide a centralized way to manage locks and synchronize access to shared resources. These services are designed to handle high concurrency and provide a robust way to coordinate access to shared resources, making it easier to prevent deadlocks and other concurrency-related issues.\n\nFor example, Redis provides a publish-subscribe model that can be used to implement a distributed lock, where a client can publish a lock request and receive a response indicating whether the lock was acquired or not. This approach can be particularly useful in a system where multiple services need to access shared resources concurrently.\n\nIn the context of your system, implementing a distributed lock service could help prevent deadlocks and other concurrency-related issues, making it easier to maintain high availability and performance under high traffic.",
